attributes.businessDescription: NVIDIA Corporation provides graphics, and compute and networking solutions in the United States, Taiwan, China, and internationally. The company’s Graphics segment offers GeForce GPUs for gaming and PCs, the GeForce NOW game streaming service and related infrastructure, and solutions for gaming platforms; Quadro/NVIDIA RTX GPUs for enterprise workstation graphics; vGPU software for cloud-based visual and virtual computing; automotive platforms for infotainment systems; and Omniverse software for building 3D designs and virtual worlds. Its Compute & Networking segment provides Data Center platforms and systems for AI, HPC, and accelerated computing; Mellanox networking and interconnect solutions; automotive AI Cockpit, autonomous driving development agreements, and autonomous vehicle solutions; cryptocurrency mining processors; Jetson for robotics and other embedded platforms; and NVIDIA AI Enterprise and other software. The company’s products are used in gaming, professional visualization, datacenter, and automotive markets. NVIDIA Corporation sells its products to original equipment manufacturers, original device manufacturers, system builders, add-in board manufacturers, retailers/distributors, independent software vendors, Internet and cloud service providers, automotive manufacturers and tier-1 automotive suppliers, mapping companies, start-ups, and other ecosystem participants. It has a strategic collaboration with Kroger Co. NVIDIA Corporation was incorporated in 1993 and is headquartered in Santa Clara, California.

attributes.content: Last close price is divided by the sum of the last 4 quarter's GAAP diluted EPS.
attributes.title: Trailing GAAP Price to Earnings Ratio:

attributes.content: The ratio of Enterprise Value to total revenue in the trailing 12 months.
attributes.title: Trailing Enterprise Value to Sales Ratio

attributes.content: The sum of actual ordinary cash dividend payments in the last 12 months divided by the last close price. Special dividends are not included in the yield. Yield (TTM) is calculated for issuers where dividend payment consistency is low, making Yield (FWD) predictions less reliable.
attributes.title: Dividend Yield (Trailing 12-months)

attributes.content: The number of years of continuous dividend growth. Dividends in a given year are calculated by the ex-dividend date, not the payment date. Only regular (not special) dividends are counted.
attributes.title: Years of Dividend Growth

attributes.content: The return on common equity is a measure of the profitability of a business in relation to the equity. ROCE is calculated as Net Income divided by Total Common Equity.
attributes.title: Return on Common Equity for Trailing 12 Month

attributes.content: Gross profit margin is calculated by subtracting the cost of goods sold from total revenue and dividing that result by total revenue.
attributes.title: Gross Profit Margin for Trailing 12 Month

attributes.content: Also known as operating income margin, operating profit margin, EBIT margin and return on sales —is the ratio of operating income to net sales.
attributes.title: EBIT Margin for Trailing 12 Month

attributes.content: Net income margin, net profit margin, or net profit ratio is calculated by finding the net profit as a percentage of the revenue, for the trailing 12 months.
attributes.title: Net income margin for trailing 12 months

attributes.content: Operating Cash is the amount of cash earned from a business's activities. It is a subtotal line item and is calculated by taking a company's net income, factoring in depreciation expenses, then adjusting for any gains or losses on sales of assets.
attributes.title: Cash From Operations (TTM)

attributes.content:
Quant Ratings are an objective, quantitative view of each stock relative to other stocks in the same sector. The ratings provide an instant summary of the available data about the stock, including the company’s financial results, the stock’s trading history, and sell-side analysts’ estimates of future revenue and earnings.

The Quant Rankings are based on the underlying rating of each stock and provides the overall rank order of the stock within the sector and overall stock universe.

For more details, see Quant Ranking and Factor Grades FAQ
attributes.title: About Quant Ratings & Rankings

attributes.content: Total Dividend for the future 12 months. It is calculated by multiplying the most recent dividend payment with the dividend payment frequency. The actual dividend over the coming 12-months may differ from Div Rate (FWD)
attributes.title: Forward Dividend Rate

attributes.content:
The dividend yield is the percentage of a company's share price that it pays out in dividends each year.

The Dividend Yield (FWD) is calculated for companies that have a consistent dividend payment policy making a forward prediction of the yield more reliable.
It is calculated as [(latest paid dividend * payment frequency) / current price].
attributes.title: Dividend Yield (FWD)

attributes.content: The dividend payout ratio is the fraction of net income a firm pays to its stockholders in dividends. This is calculated as the ratio of Dividend per share to Earnings Per share.
attributes.title: Cash Dividend Payout Ratio

attributes.content: Last close price divided by the next fiscal year consensus non-GAAP EPS estimate (FY1). Non-GAAP EPS is normalized based on analysts' methodology. Read more here.
attributes.title: Forward Non-GAAP Price to Earnings Ratio:

attributes.content:
Seeking Alpha’s Quant Dividend Grades provide an instant characterization of each stock’s dividend strength or weakness compared to its relative sector. Dividend Safety measures profitability and leverage metrics. The Yield Grade measures historical and consensus estimated yield. Dividend Growth measures historical and estimated growth rates. Dividend Consistency measures how consistently the company has paid a dividend and raised its dividend. In combination, the Dividend Grades help investors assess if the dividend is safe and if income will be stable, increase, or decrease.

For more details, see Dividend Grades FAQ

See an informative video interview with the creator of the Seeking Alpha Quant System on the Best ways to use the Dividend Grades(Video)
attributes.title: About Dividend Grades

attributes.content: The ratio of current price to the Book Value in trailing 12 months
attributes.title: Trailing Price to Book Value Ratio

attributes.content: The ratio of current Enterprise Value to the total EBITDA in the trailing 12 months
attributes.title: Trailing Enterprise Value to EBITDA Ratio

attributes.content: The last dividend paid multiplied with the payment frequency. A forward-looking amount that is calculated for consistent dividend payers. Special Dividends are excluded from this calculation.
attributes.title: Annual Payout (FWD)

attributes.content: The 5-year compounded annual growth rate in dividends paid.
attributes.title: 5 Year Growth Rate (CAGR)

attributes.content:
Market cap—or market capitalization—refers to the total value of all a company's shares of stock. It is calculated by multiplying the price of a stock by its total number of outstanding shares.

Market Capitalization (Implied) is a public company’s total equity value as implied by the stock’s last observed trading price. Unlike the standard calculation of market cap, Market Capitalization (Implied) includes an adjustment for shares held by limted partners and restricted share classes, when applicable.

Implied market capitalization is prioritized whenever applicable.

Note: For ADRs, market cap is based off of the primary listing of the company.
attributes.title: Market Capitalization

attributes.content: Total Debt is the sum of Long Term and Short Term debt of the company. This includes Short-term Borrowings, Current Portion of Long-Term Debt, Current Portion of Cap. Leases, Long-Term Debt, Capital Leases among others.
attributes.title: Total Debt of the company

attributes.content: Cash & Cash Equivalents include Cash And Equivalents (Balance Sheet Item), Short Term Investments, and Trading Asset Securities
attributes.title: Cash & Cash Equivalents

attributes.content: Enterprise value or Firm Value is a measure of a company's total value, that includes in its calculation the market capitalization of a company but also short-term and long-term debt as well as any cash on the company's balance sheet.
attributes.title: Enterprise Value

attributes.content: Short interest is the percentage of share float that has been sold short but has not yet been covered or closed out. Short interest is an indicator of market sentiment. Extremely high short interest shows investors are very pessimistic.
attributes.title: Short Interest

attributes.content: The short interest ratio represents the number of days it takes short sellers on average to close their positions, i.e. repurchase all of the borrowed shares. It is calculated by dividing the number of shares sold short by the average daily trading volume over the last 30 days.
attributes.title: Days to Cover / Short interest Ratio

attributes.content: Beta is a measure of the volatility of a security/portfolio compared to the market as a whole. The market has a beta of 1.0, and individual stocks are ranked according to how much they deviate from the market. 24M Beta is the Beta over the past 24-months.
attributes.title: 24M Beta

attributes.content: The Altman Z Score may be used to predict the probability that a firm will go into bankruptcy within two years. It uses profitability, leverage, liquidity, solvency, and activity to predict whether a company has a high probability of becoming insolvent. A score below 1.8 means it's likely the company is headed for bankruptcy, while companies with scores above 3 are not likely to go bankrupt.
attributes.title: Altman Z Score

attributes.content:
Growth in Diluted Earnings per Share, Year-over-Year.
Diluted EPS represents a company's earnings performance if all of its outstanding convertible securities were exercised. Diluted EPS is considered a conservative metric because it indicates a worst-case scenario in terms of EPS.
attributes.title: EPS Diluted (YoY)

attributes.content: Compounded annual growth in Diluted Earnings per Share over the last 3 years.

attributes.content:
Growth in Levered Free Cash Flow, Year-over-Year.
Levered Free Cash Flow is the amount of cash a business has after it has met its financial obligations like operating expenses and interest payments. It is the amount of cash that a company can use to pay dividends and make investments in the business.
attributes.title: Levered FCF (YoY)

attributes.content:
Factor Grades provide investors with an instant characterization of each stock. This makes it easy to find or rule out stocks based on your investment criteria.

Seeking Alpha grades each stock by five “factors” -- Value, Growth, Profitability, Momentum and EPS Revisions. To do this, we compare the relevant metrics for the factor in question for the stock to the same metrics for the other stocks in its sector. The factor is then assigned a grade, from A+ to F.

For more details, see Quant Ranking and Factor Grades FAQ

See an informative video with the creator of the Seeking Alpha Quant System on the best ways to use the Quant Rankings and Factor Grades An Interview With The Founder Of The Seeking Alpha Quant Rating System (Video)
attributes.title: About Factor Grades

attributes.content: Previous day exchange-traded volume of the ticker.

attributes.content:
The dividend yield is a financial ratio that tells you the percentage of a company's share price that it pays out in dividends each year.

In this table, The Dividend Yield (FWD) is an aggregate of the Analyst estimate of yield on the stock, in the upcoming year.
attributes.title: Dividend Yield (FWD) - (Estimate) or Dividend Yield (FWD) - Est.

attributes.content: Forward Price-To-Earnings Ratio is a forward looking version of the conventional P/E ratio that uses forecasted earnings for the P/E calculation. Since P/E (FWD) uses estimated earnings, the actual P/E over the coming 12-months may differ. It is used to value companies at their future level of earnings.
attributes.title: Forward Price-To-Earnings Ratio

attributes.content:
Forward earnings per share are an estimate of the next period's earnings of a company.

Forward earnings are modeled by analysts, often with guidance from management, that will project near-term revenues, margins, tax rates, and other financial data for investors and investment analysts.
attributes.title: Forward Earnings per Share

attributes.content: Price to earnings ratio is calculated by dividing the current price per share by the earnings per share of the trailing 12-months. The ratio is based on actual observed data and it is an important valuation tool.
attributes.title: Price-To-Earnings Ratio

attributes.content: The lowest and highest price at which a ticker has traded during the previous 52 weeks
attributes.title: 52-week range

attributes.content: The lowest and highest price at which a ticker has traded during the previous trading day
attributes.title: Previous Day Range

attributes.content: Earnings per share is calculated by dividing the earnings of a ticker by the basic-weighted average of shares outstanding for that period. EPS TTM is arrived at by summing the EPS for each of the four preceding quarters. The data is based on actual results declared by the company.
attributes.title: Earnings Per Share for Trailing 12-months

attributes.content: This is calculated by summing up the actual dividends paid by the issuer in the preceding 12-months. Dividend rate TTM is calculated for issuers where dividend payment consistency is low, making forward assumptions less reliable.
attributes.title: Dividend Rate (Trailing 12-months)

attributes.content: The sum of actual ordinary cash dividend payments in the last 12 months divided by the last close price. Special dividends are not included in the yield. Yield (TTM) is calculated for issuers where dividend payment consistency is low, making Yield (FWD) predictions less reliable.
attributes.title: Dividend Yield (Trailing 12-months)

attributes.content: The number of shares sold short but have not yet been covered or closed out.
attributes.title: Shares Short

attributes.content:
The number of shares outstanding for the referenced class of securities of the company. (Ex. Class A, Class B shares Etc.)

This is different than Shares Outstanding (Company), which is the total of all classes of shares outstanding for the company, wherever applicable.
attributes.title: Shares Outstanding (Ticker)

attributes.content:
The conventional Price-to-Earnings ratio, which uses the current Price per share over the Earnings per shares (EPS) from the trailing 12 months.
The ratio is used for valuing companies and to find out whether they are overvalued or undervalued.
attributes.title: Trailing 12-months P/E Ratio

attributes.content: The ETF Liquidity grades generally shows how quickly shares of an ETF can be bought or sold without substantially impacting the ETF share price. For institutional orders, ETFs with low liquidity may be difficult to sell and may require being sold over a number of days to avoid market impact. For most individual investors, in regards to execution, liquidity is not a major factor. However, large institutions can impact the share price with their order flow where liquidity is limited. The Liquidity grade is a blend of liquidity metrics. An ETF with a Seeking Alpha Liquidity Grade of A+ is very attractive and is viewed as having better liquidity compared to the overall universe of ETFs.
attributes.title: About ETF Factor Grades

attributes.content:
Market Capitalization (Implied) is a public company’s total equity value as implied by the stock’s last observed trading price. Unlike the standard calculation of market cap, Market Capitalization (Implied) includes an adjustment for shares held by limited partners and restricted share classes, when applicable.

Note: For ADRs, market cap is based off of the primary listing of the company.

attributes.content: The return on assets shows the percentage of how profitable a company's assets are in generating revenue. It is calculated as net income divided by average total assets.

attributes.content: The date on which the company pays out the proportion of earnings paid out as dividends to shareholders.

attributes.content: Dividend frequency is how often a dividend is paid by an individual stock or fund.
attributes.title: Dividend Frequency

attributes.content: Asset Under Management (AUM) is the total market value of the investments that are held by a fund.
attributes.title: Asset Under Management

attributes.content: Earnings per share (EPS) is a company's net profit divided by the number of common shares it has outstanding.
attributes.title: Earnings per share (EPS)

attributes.content: The P/E ratio simply the stock price divided by the company's earnings per share
attributes.title: P/E Ratio

attributes.content: TTM Revenue describes the revenue that a company earns over the trailing 12 months (TTM) of business.
attributes.title: Revenue (TTM)

attributes.content: Revenue per Share is the amount of Revenue per outstanding share of the company's stock.
attributes.title: Revenue Per Share

attributes.content: This value denote the revenue left after paying all direct production expenses.
attributes.title: Gross Profit (TTM)

attributes.content: It is the earnings of the company before netting interest, taxes, and depreciation & amortization components for the past twelve consecutive months.
attributes.title: EBITDA (TTM)

attributes.content: This value is the Income After Taxes for the trailing twelve months.
attributes.title: Net Income (TTM)

attributes.content: This is calculated by dividing net income net of preferred dividends by a weighted average of total shares outstanding plus additional common shares that would have been outstanding if the dilutive common share would have been issued for the trailing 12 months.
attributes.title: EPS Diluted (TTM)

attributes.content: This is the Total Cash plus Short Term Investments divided by the Shares Outstanding at the end of the most recent quarter.
attributes.title: Total Cash (MRQ)

attributes.content: Cash per share is calculated by dividing cash on hand by the total number of shares.
attributes.title: Total Cash Per Share

attributes.content: Total debt is the sum of all long-term liabilities and is identified on the company's balance sheet.
attributes.title: Total Debt (MRQ)

attributes.content: Total Debt for the most recent interim period divided by Total Shareholder Equity for the same period.
attributes.title: Total Debt to Equity (MRQ)

attributes.content: This is the ratio of Total Current Assets for the most recent interim period divided by Total Current Liabilities for the same period.
attributes.title: Current Ratio (MRQ)

attributes.content: It is defined as Total Current Assets minus Total Inventory for the most recent interim period divided by Total Current Liabilities for the same period.
attributes.title: Quick Ratio (MRQ)

attributes.content: It is calculated as Net Debt divided by Equity.
attributes.title: Total Debt / Equity (MRQ)

attributes.content: Total Debt To Capital is a leverage ratio. It is calculated as Net Debt divided by Total Capital.
attributes.title: Total Debt / Capital (MRQ)

attributes.content: This ratio is Total Debt for the most recent interim period divided by Total Shareholder Equity for the same period.
attributes.title: LT Debt / Equity (MRQ)

attributes.content: This ratio is Total Debt for the most recent interim period divided by Total capital for the same period.
attributes.title: LT Debt / Total Capital (MRQ)

attributes.content: The Total liabilities to Total assets ratio is a solvency ratio that examines how much of a company's assets are made of liabilities
attributes.title: Total Liabilities / Total Assets (MRQ)

attributes.content: Turnover is a measurement to describe a fund’s annual trading activity. It is a percentage used to demonstrate how many holdings a mutual fund or exchange-traded funds (ETF) were replaced within the year.

Investing activities include purchases of physical assets, investments in securities, or the sale of securities or assets. of physical assets, investments in securities, or the sale of securities or assets.

attributes.content: Levered free cash flow (LFCF) is the amount of money a company has left remaining after paying all of its financial obligations over the trailing twelve months. LFCF is the amount of cash a company has after paying debts.Levered free cash flow (LFCF) is the amount of money a company has left remaining after paying all of its financial obligations. LFCF is the amount of cash a company has after paying debts.
attributes.title: Levered Free Cash Flow (TTM)

attributes.content: Unlevered free cash flow (UFCF) is the amount of available cash a firm has before accounting for its financial obligations over the trailing twelve months.
attributes.title: Unlevered Free Cash Flow (TTM)

attributes.content:
Free cash flow per share (FCF) is a measure of a company's financial flexibility that is determined by dividing free cash flow by the total number of shares outstanding.

This measure serves as a proxy for measuring changes in earnings per share.
attributes.title: Free Cash Flow / Share (TTM)

attributes.content:
The EPS Revision grade measures the company’s EPS revisions relative to other stocks in its sector. Sell-side analysts estimate companies’ future revenues and earnings, and may revise upward or downward their estimates.

The EPS revisions score is derived from revisions to analysts’ estimates for the current year in the last 90 days. It is measured a scale of 1-3, where the closer a revision mark is to 1 the more strongly analysts have revised their estimates up over the last 90 days, and the closer to 3 the the more strongly analysts have revised their estimates down over the last 90 days.

The EPS revisions grade is derived from a comparison of the aggregate of all the underlying metrics, and is therefore not an average of the grades for each underlying metric.
attributes.title: FY1 Up Revisions

attributes.content:
The EPS Revision grade measures the company’s EPS revisions relative to other stocks in its sector. Sell-side analysts estimate companies’ future revenues and earnings, and may revise upward or downward their estimates.

The EPS revisions score is derived from revisions to analysts’ estimates for the current year in the last 90 days. It is measured a scale of 1-3, where the closer a revision mark is to 1 the more strongly analysts have revised their estimates up over the last 90 days, and the closer to 3 the the more strongly analysts have revised their estimates down over the last 90 days.

The EPS revisions grade is derived from a comparison of the aggregate of all the underlying metrics, and is therefore not an average of the grades for each underlying metric.
attributes.title: FY1 Down Revisions

attributes.content: Funds from operations forward, or FFO (FWD), refers to the figure used by real estate investment trusts (REITs) to define the cash flow from their operations for the next fiscal year.
attributes.title: FFO (FWD)

attributes.content: Last close price divided by the next fiscal year consensus for FFO. Price to Funds From Operations (FFO) ratio is a valution metric. Analysts calculate FFO as reported by companies. The calculation is last close price divided by the next fiscal year consensus FFO estimate (FY1).
attributes.title: P/FFO (FWD)

attributes.content: The turnover ratio or turnover rate is the percentage of a mutual fund or other portfolio's holdings that have been replaced in a given year.
attributes.title: Turnover Ratio

attributes.content: Net assets are the value of a company's assets minus its liabilities. It is calculated ((Total Fixed Assets + Total Current Assets) – (Total Current Liabilities + Total Long Term Liabilities)).
attributes.title: Net Assets

attributes.content: An “index fund” is a type of mutual fund or exchange-traded fund that seeks to track the returns of a market index.
attributes.title: Index Fund

attributes.content: A fund that does not charge any type of sales load. But not every type of shareholder fee is a "sales load," and a no-load fund may charge fees that are not sales loads. No-load funds also charge operating expenses.
attributes.title: No Load Fund

attributes.content: The price/earnings ratio (Non-GAAP) is often referred to as P/E (Non-GAAP TTM) and is calculated as the stock's current price, divided by a company's trailing 12-month earnings per share (EPS) based on Non-GAAP financial reporting.
attributes.title: P/E Non-GAAP (TTM)

attributes.content:
The ETF Asset Flow grades the movement of cash into and out of ETFs. Flows do not reflect the performance of the investment. They reflect how investors move capital in and out of the fund.
The Asset Flow grade is a blend of % change in Assets under management over designated time periods and average daily share volume. An ETF with a Seeking Alpha Asset Flow Grade of A+ is very attractive and is viewed as having better asset flows and volume compared to the overall universe of ETFs.
attributes.title: Asset Flows

attributes.content: The expense ratio is the cost of owning a mutual fund or exchange-traded fund (ETF). The expense ratio is measured as a percent of your investment in the fund. A stock with a Seeking Alpha Expense Ratio of A+ is very attractive and is viewed as having a better expense ratio compared to the overall universe of ETFs.
attributes.title: Expenses Ratio

attributes.content:
This factor refers to an ETFs velocity of price change compared to the sector as opposed to the actual price levels themselves. Momentum is measured by continually taking price differences for a fixed time period.
Seeking Alpha incorporates and combines different time periods into this grade. An ETF with a Seeking Alpha Momentum Grade of A+ is very attractive and is viewed as having better price action compared to the overall universe of ETFs.
attributes.title: Momentum Grade

attributes.content: Unannualized Turnover is a measurement to describe a fund’s trading activity other than one year, whether it be a week, month, quarter or several years.. It is a percentage used to demonstrate how many holdings a mutual fund or exchange-traded funds (ETF) were replaced.
attributes.title: Unannualized Turnover Ratio

attributes.content: Preferred debt gotta go bye bye, then all good

@Tradedollarnut

Good to see you in this comment section. Would you share your thoughts on how to value this company?

It would also be helpful if you would share your insights on the pace for redeeming or calling the preferred vs additional distribution increases.

I think I understand the significant call premium ($1,800 for $1,000 par) and the idea that it ratchets down 3% each quarter with the cash payment of pfd. dividend.

It seems like the preferred is clearly next up for retirement after the remainder of the 2025 9.125% Notes are called at the end of this month. In the latest earnings transcript, I read that the company can call or redeem the $250 million of preferred in tranches of $25 million. So perhaps, we will see some preferred calls later in this quarter or early next year. Additional distributions would also seem to be possible.

Thanks for sharing your thinking.

@sapient they will redeem the preferred in 2 years and not before because of the intricacies of the agreement. That was evident when they repaid their 2025 bonds. It’s going to take all their free cashflow from the next two years to service the debt, pay distributions and build up the preferred repayment fund. That limits their value.

Right now they are valued at book essentially [subtract preferred but add market value delta to Wyoming] and sadly I don’t think they’re undervalued compared to the coal companies. This company may be a buy in 18 months or on a dip into the low $30’s but is fairly valued right now at $40 in this market.

@Tradedollarnut

That is very helpful. Thank you.

Yes, it looks like NRP will need the majority ($100 million) of the new credit line plus cash on hand for the call on October 31 of the remaining $140 million or so in 9.125% 2025 Notes. Then, I don’t think they can or will early call any of the other $100 million or so in Opco debt.

I was just wondering if they might call a couple $25 million tranches of the preferred as they generate cash. It seems that NRP should be generating $50 million in FCF per quarter. I still think they could do that vs. pay down the credit line or boost the distribution. It will be interesting to see the rate and terms on the new credit line.

api_list.code:
import requests

url = "https://seeking-alpha-finance.p.rapidapi.com/v1/markets/day-watch"

headers = {
            "X-RapidAPI-Key": "SIGN-UP-FOR-KEY",
            "X-RapidAPI-Host": "seeking-alpha-finance.p.rapidapi.com"
        }

response = requests.get(url, headers=headers)
print(response.json())

attributes.bio:
I am a market enthusiast and part-time trader. I started writing for Seeking Alpha in 2011, and it has been a tremendous opportunity and learning experience. I have been interested in the markets since elementary school, and hope to pursue a career in the investment management industry. I have been active in the markets for several years, and am primarily focused on long/short equities. I hold a Bachelor of Science Degree from Lehigh University, where I double majored in Finance and Accounting, with a minor in History. My major track focused on Investments and Financial Analysis. While at Lehigh, I was the Head Portfolio Manager of the Investment Management Group, a student group that manages three portfolios, one long/short and two long only. I have had two internships, one a summer internship at a large bank, and another helping to manage the Lehigh University Endowment for nearly a year.


Disclaimer: Bill reminds investors to always do their own due diligence on any investment, and to consult their own financial adviser or representative when necessary. Any material provided is intended as general information only, and should not be considered or relied upon as a formal investment recommendation.

attributes.title: Lumen Technologies: Searching For A Bottom

attributes.content:
@Justin Wiedeman

Just to note - at the end of Q4 they were NOT above the highest leverage ratio. They were only paying the 2% spread on the first term loans, where if they go over the high bar it moves to 2.25%. Of course, there are multiple term loans and not all of them have the same terms and / or spreads.

Also, 1-Month LIBOR hit a new high today, over 4.87%.

As for the tender, yes, I ran all the numbers based on the results, the series caps, and such. Obviously the $11 million is not the final number since more debt can be tendered (with lower compensation for the holders).
